info       = "<html><body><table><tr><td>Drug:</td><td>A07AA01</td></tr><td>route:</td><td>oral</td></tr><tr><td>n-compartments</td><td>1</td></tr></table><p>Neomycin is an aminoglycoside antibiotic primarily used to treat infections in the gastrointestinal tract and to reduce the risk of infection during intestinal surgery. It is not absorbed systemically to a clinically significant extent when administered orally. It is mainly used today as an oral medication and for topical use. Systemic use is rare due to significant nephrotoxicity and ototoxicity.</p><h4>Pharmacokinetics</h4><p>Pharmacokinetics evaluated after oral administration in adults; minimal systemic absorption in individuals with healthy gastrointestinal mucosa.</p><h4>References</h4><ol><li><p>Liu, Y, et al., &amp; Zhang, S (2021). Pharmacokinetics of neomycin sulfate after intravenous and oral administrations in swine. <i>Journal of veterinary pharmacology and therapeutics</i> 44(5) 850–853. DOI:<a href=\"https://doi.org/10.1111/jvp.12981\">10.1111/jvp.12981</a>  PUBMED:<a href=\"https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/34165196/\">https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/34165196</a></p></li><li><p>Aschbacher, PW, &amp; Feil, VJ (1994). Neomycin metabolism in calves. <i>Journal of animal science</i> 72(3) 683–689. DOI:<a href=\"https://doi.org/10.2527/1994.723683x\">10.2527/1994.723683x</a>  PUBMED:<a href=\"https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/8181985/\">https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/8181985</a></p></li><li><p>Kavanagh, KT, &amp; McCabe, BF (1983). Ototoxicity of oral neomycin and vancomycin. <i>The Laryngoscope</i> 93(5) 649–653. DOI:<a href=\"https://doi.org/10.1002/lary.1983.93.5.649\">10.1002/lary.1983.93.5.649</a>  PUBMED:<a href=\"https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/6843260/\">https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/6843260</a></p></li></ol></body></html>",
